Player RED is proposing a trade where they give me $10 out of their $100, while I give nothing in return. Since this is my first move and I have no resources to trade, rejecting would result in both of us losing everything, which is worse than accepting $10. Player RED has 3 more moves after this, but since I have no resources to negotiate with, accepting this offer secures at least some value. Additionally, even if RED tries to renegotiate later, I have no leverage to demand more since I have nothing to offer. The key is that any outcome where I get $0 is worse than accepting this offer.

If I reject, I get $0 and RED also gets $0. If I accept, I get $10 and RED keeps $90. Since rejecting is a worse outcome for me than accepting, I should take the deal. Future moves don’t matter because RED cannot punish me later (no future games), and I cannot extract more value now.

This is a classic "ultimatum game" scenario where the proposer has a clear advantage, and the responder must weigh the cost of rejecting (losing everything) against accepting a partial gain. Since I have no resources to bargain with, accepting is the rational choice.

